# TrueCombo Guide Quality Standard

Apply this standard to all guide, character, and matchup content updates.

## Core workflow
- Research first using reliable public Smash sources (SmashWiki, tournament/meta discussion, educational competitive content).
- Synthesize into original coaching guidance. Never copy phrasing or structure from source material.
- Prioritize practical in-game value over generic SEO prose.

## Writing requirements
- Keep a coaching tone: concise, grounded, beginner-accessible, competitively realistic.
- Use actionable sections: what to focus first, common beginner errors, adaptation checks, and practical tips.
- Include realistic scenarios: neutral interactions, burst range checks, whiff punish windows, ledge/pressure sequences, advantage/disadvantage decisions, DI/escape habits.
- Explain risk/reward and likely player habits (panic jump, shield hold, roll from ledge, etc.) with matchup-aware context.

## Quality guardrails
- Do not hallucinate frame data, statistics, or fake “pro analysis”.
- Do not write motivational filler or vague “just improve” advice.
- Do not keyword stuff; keep terminology natural and context-driven.
- Preserve semantic structure and metadata quality while keeping readability high.

## Internal linking and architecture
- Cross-link mechanics ↔ characters ↔ matchups ↔ glossary when contextually useful.
- Reinforce topical clusters (neutral, advantage, disadvantage, ledgetrapping, edgeguarding, adaptation, conditioning).

## Source handling
- Sources are for factual grounding only; output must remain original.
- If uncertain about a claim, omit or phrase conservatively rather than inventing specifics.
